<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Bihar</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">Cradle of <em>Civilization & Spirituality</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Bihar, one of the oldest inhabited places on earth, is the cradle of some of humanity's greatest civilizations and spiritual traditions. The birthplace of Buddhism and Jainism, Bihar nurtured Siddhartha Gautama's enlightenment under the Bodhi Tree at Bodh Gaya and Lord Mahavira's birth at Vaishali. Home to the ancient Nalanda University — the world's first residential university — Bihar has been the seat of learning, philosophy and statecraft for over 2,500 years. The mighty Maurya and Gupta empires that once unified much of the Indian subcontinent were born in this sacred land. The Ganges and its tributaries weave through Bihar's fertile plains, nourishing fields of rice and wheat while carrying the prayers of millions. From the prehistoric caves of Kaimur to the living traditions of Chhath Puja — a festival older than recorded history — Bihar pulses with an energy that connects the ancient world to the present. Its people, the Bihari diaspora spread across every corner of India and the world, carry this civilizational pride wherever they go. Bihar today stands as a land of paradoxes: ancient ruins alongside bustling cities, profound spirituality beside commercial energy, rural simplicity alongside intellectual ambition.</p>
</section>

